2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinic semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O3/c5-3-1-2-4(6)7/h3H,1-2H2,(H,6,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-4-cyanobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHNO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"isocyanic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHNO/c2-1-3/h(H,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,5-diamino-5-oxopentanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2O3/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H2,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions; H2-rich, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 through iron-sulfur mediated electron transfer to produce formate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Consistent with iron-sulfur world CO2 reduction chemistry and vent-interface formate generation, with greigite/mackinawite as required hydrothermal mineral agents; formate is also a known product in serpentinization-linked CO2 fixation systems (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Kitadai, 2015; Preiner et al., 2020; Beyazay et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reduction from formate/CO2 to acetate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal vent or subseafloor setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation on metal-rich mineral surfaces gives acetate-like C2 products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Supported by serpentinization-linked and hydrothermal carbon fixation literature that yields acetate/formate from CO2 and H2 on Fe/Ni-bearing catalysts; included here to connect hydrothermal carbon fixation to pyruvate production and cross-environment carbon flow (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020; Beyazay et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"serpentinization-linked H2-rich system; pyruvate observed in awaruite/serpentinization analog chemistry near 100C\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive carbon fixation extends C2 intermediates to C3 alpha-keto acids on reduced iron-bearing mineral surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is an experimentally observed product of H2-dependent CO2 fixation under serpentinization-related catalysis, linking hydrothermal carbon fixation to metabolic keto acids (Preiner et al., 2020; Beyazay et al., 2023). Mineral assignments follow the required hydrothermal mineral set while preserving literature-consistent vent chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface generation of glyoxylate from simple amino acid precursor network\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343-353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2/phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"warm surface pool; phosphate-assisted chemistry analogous to glycine/serine-derived glyoxylate-pyruvate network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Surface redox and rearrangement chemistry in phosphate-bearing pools generates glyoxylate as a C2 alpha-oxoacid node.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate is a key prebiotic precursor to alpha-ketoglutarate and is implicated in nonenzymatic protometabolic networks; the direct transformation shown here is a connective abstraction to keep the graph fully linked, grounded in the broader glyoxylate/pyruvate protometabolic chemistry rather than a single-step definitive synthesis (Stubbs et al., 2020; Ter-Ovanessian et al., 2025). Because this is a surface-environment connector, TiO2 and phosphate minerals are specified as required agents; this step is partially speculative.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface aldol coupling of glyoxylate and pyruvate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration by borate/clay surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 4.5 to 5; warm evaporitic or geothermal pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nonenzymatic aldol addition/cross-Cannizzaro-like network between glyoxylate and pyruvate forms the C5 alpha-keto diacid alpha-ketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly based on the nonenzymatic ancestral Krebs-cycle analog where glyoxylate and pyruvate generate alpha-ketoglutarate under mild acidic warm conditions; mineral surfaces here are included as concentrators required by the network schema, not because the original report required them (Stubbs et al., 2020; Mayer & Moran, 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K to 323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high H2 partial pressure\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/FeS2 analog mineral catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"ammonium present; pH near 8 for high-yield Ni systems, with FeS-based precedent for hydrothermal reductive amination\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia adds to the alpha-keto acid followed by mineral-assisted reduction of the imine/iminium to the alpha-amino acid glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is the best-established prebiotic route to glutamate. Kaur et al. showed alpha-ketoglutarate reductive amination to glutamate at 22C, pH 8 with H2 and Ni/SiO2-Al2O3; earlier FeS/H2S and FeS/Fe(OH)2 work established hydrothermal mineral reductive amination of alpha-oxo acids. The network uses FeS/pyrite-class hydrothermal minerals to satisfy the required environment-mineral constraint while retaining literature grounding (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; Kaur et al., 2024; Nogal et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate with glycine to glutamic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Al3+ in solution; mineral surfaces as concentrators\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 5; metal-ion-catalyzed transamination regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Amino transfer from glycine to alpha-ketoglutarate forms glutamate within a nonenzymatic transamination network, with glyoxylate regenerated.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly based on the ancestral Krebs-cycle analog showing alpha-ketoglutarate plus glycine gives glutamate in 44% yield at 80C and pH 5 with Al3+ catalysis; glyoxylate is regenerated within the network. Surface minerals are included as concentration/templating agents required by the schema, though soluble Al3+ is the key catalyst in the literature (Degani & Halmann, 1967; Stubbs et al., 2020; Muchowska et al., 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN-based formation of succinic semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-photochemical mineral assistance\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"electric discharge/photochemical atmosphere-ocean transfer analog; strongly reducing/anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN-rich photochemical and atmospheric chemistry generates higher aldehydes including C4 carbonyls that partition into aqueous surface reservoirs.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature identifies succinic semialdehyde as the required Strecker aldehyde precursor for glutamate, and Miller-type discharge chemistry is the best-supported source of C4 aldehydes/semialdehydes in prebiotic inventories, although no direct dedicated prebiotic synthesis of this precursor was demonstrated. This connecting step is therefore literature-motivated but partly speculative (Miller, 1955; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of glutamate aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration in aqueous pool\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"classical Strecker regime in anoxic waters\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine/hemiaminal, then cyanide addition gives the alpha-aminonitrile precursor to glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the literature-supported mechanistic logic for Miller-Urey amino acid synthesis, specifically extended to glutamate via the required aldehyde succinic semialdehyde. The report notes that this exact glutamate Strecker route remains plausible but not directly demonstrated from prebiotically sourced succinic semialdehyde, so this step is necessary but partly speculative (Miller, 1955; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of glutamate aminonitrile to glutamic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted hydrolysis/concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"extended aqueous aging or wet-dry cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aminonitrile hydrolyzes through amide intermediates to the corresponding amino acid glutamic acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of Strecker aminonitriles to amino acids is the accepted downstream step in spark-discharge amino acid synthesis and explains glutamate recovery after hydrolysis-based analyses. Specific isolation of glutamate aminonitrile has not been reported in the cited studies, so this node is a mechanistic reconstruction required to connect literature routes (Miller, 1955; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of HCN polymer to glutamic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV exposure and mineral adsorption\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"HCN oligomerization/polymer hydrolysis in acidic or basic workup\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN oligomerization yields polymeric nitrile-rich solids that release amino acids including glutamic acid upon hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Directly grounded in the classic HCN polymer literature and later reviews showing glutamic acid among hydrolysis products of HCN-derived polymers, while acknowledging product assignments can be analytically challenging (Matthews & Moser, 1967; Ferris, Sanchez & Orgel, 1966-1978; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013; Cleaves et al., 2010).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/prebiotic amidation of glutamic acid to glutamine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\"null\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none demonstrated\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"speculative cyanate-activated amidation in concentrated pool; competing cyclization to pyroglutamate expected\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Putative activation of the gamma-carboxyl of glutamic acid by cyanate-derived mixed anhydride or intramolecular anhydride chemistry followed by ammonolysis to give the side-chain amide.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the unresolved bottleneck. The literature states that no prebiotic experiment has demonstrated glutamine formation, and cyanate-mediated activation of dicarboxylic acids is identified as the most promising but undemonstrated route. This reaction is therefore explicitly speculative and included only because the user requested a network to glutamine (Danger et al., 2012; Leman et al., 2004; Weber & Miller, 1981; Higgs & Pudritz, 2009; de Carvalho Fernandes et al., 2022).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal carbon fixation to reductive amination route\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is reduced hydrothermally to formate and acetate, extended to pyruvate, coupled with glyoxylate on the surface to alpha-ketoglutarate, then reductively aminated to glutamate and speculatively amidated to glutamine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-glyoxylate aldol plus transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate feeds surface aldol formation of alpha-ketoglutarate, which undergoes nonenzymatic transamination with glycine to glutamate before speculative amidation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate-assisted protometabolic route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formate enters a surface protometabolic network to glyoxylate, then alpha-ketoglutarate, glutamate, and finally speculative glutamine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker route from HCN and succinic semialdehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface HCN chemistry supplies succinic semialdehyde, which undergoes Strecker synthesis to glutamate aminonitrile and hydrolysis to glutamate, followed by speculative amidation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN polymer hydrolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN oligomerization/polymerization produces glutamic acid upon hydrolysis, which then faces the unresolved amidation bottleneck to glutamine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate reductive amination minimal route\",\n      \"description\": \"Once alpha-ketoglutarate is available from pyruvate and glyoxylate, hydrothermal reductive amination gives glutamate, followed by speculative cyanate-mediated amidation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate transamination minimal route\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate formed on the surface is converted to glutamate by glycine-dependent transamination, then speculatively amidated.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface mixed route via acetate and pyruvate\",\n      \"description\": \"A longer mixed-environment path in which hydrothermal acetate and pyruvate production feed surface alpha-ketoglutarate formation and then glutamate synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate to surface alpha-ketoglutarate to transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate enters the surface aldol network to alpha-ketoglutarate and then the transamination branch to glutamate and speculative glutamine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Convergent glutamate pool route\",\n      \"description\": \"Multiple glutamate-producing routes converge into a common glutamate reservoir, any of which could in principle feed the unresolved final amidation step to glutamine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Glutamine", "overall_strategy": "This network is literature-guided and explicitly reflects that glutamine is not a demonstrated prebiotic product. The network therefore builds a connected bipartite synthesis graph in which multiple experimentally supported routes converge on glutamic acid through the central hub alpha-ketoglutarate, while the final conversion to glutamine is represented only as speculative, low-plausibility amidation chemistry motivated by cyanate/phosphate activation analogies discussed in the literature. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies formate, acetate, pyruvate, and reductive amination routes; surface chemistry supplies glyoxylate, HCN-derived precursors, Strecker-type access to glutamate, and activation chemistry; biochemical/prebiotic settings host transamination, condensation, and the undemonstrated final amidation. The graph contains 10 distinct pathway variants to the target, most of which share the same unresolved final bottleneck from glutamic acid to glutamine.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CH2O2", "iupac_name": "methanoic acid", "common_name": "formate/formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "acetic acid", "common_name": "acetate/acetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid/glutamate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H6O3", "iupac_name": "4-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "succinic semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O3/c5-3-1-2-4(6)7/h3H,1-2H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H8N2O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-4-cyanobutanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "isocyanic acid", "common_name": "cyanate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHNO/c2-1-3/h(H,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H8N2O3", "iupac_name": "2,5-diamino-5-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2O3/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H2,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions; H2-rich, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 through iron-sulfur mediated electron transfer to produce formate.", "reasoning": "Consistent with iron-sulfur world CO2 reduction chemistry and vent-interface formate generation, with greigite/mackinawite as required hydrothermal mineral agents; formate is also a known product in serpentinization-linked CO2 fixation systems (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Kitadai, 2015; Preiner et al., 2020; Beyazay et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal reduction from formate/CO2 to acetate", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal vent or subseafloor setting"}, "mechanism": "Sequential CO2 reduction and C-C bond formation on metal-rich mineral surfaces gives acetate-like C2 products.", "reasoning": "Supported by serpentinization-linked and hydrothermal carbon fixation literature that yields acetate/formate from CO2 and H2 on Fe/Ni-bearing catalysts; included here to connect hydrothermal carbon fixation to pyruvate production and cross-environment carbon flow (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020; Beyazay et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "serpentinization-linked H2-rich system; pyruvate observed in awaruite/serpentinization analog chemistry near 100C"}, "mechanism": "Reductive carbon fixation extends C2 intermediates to C3 alpha-keto acids on reduced iron-bearing mineral surfaces.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is an experimentally observed product of H2-dependent CO2 fixation under serpentinization-related catalysis, linking hydrothermal carbon fixation to metabolic keto acids (Preiner et al., 2020; Beyazay et al., 2023). Mineral assignments follow the required hydrothermal mineral set while preserving literature-consistent vent chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Surface generation of glyoxylate from simple amino acid precursor network", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343-353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2/phosphate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "warm surface pool; phosphate-assisted chemistry analogous to glycine/serine-derived glyoxylate-pyruvate network"}, "mechanism": "Surface redox and rearrangement chemistry in phosphate-bearing pools generates glyoxylate as a C2 alpha-oxoacid node.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate is a key prebiotic precursor to alpha-ketoglutarate and is implicated in nonenzymatic protometabolic networks; the direct transformation shown here is a connective abstraction to keep the graph fully linked, grounded in the broader glyoxylate/pyruvate protometabolic chemistry rather than a single-step definitive synthesis (Stubbs et al., 2020; Ter-Ovanessian et al., 2025). Because this is a surface-environment connector, TiO2 and phosphate minerals are specified as required agents; this step is partially speculative."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface aldol coupling of glyoxylate and pyruvate to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration by borate/clay surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 4.5 to 5; warm evaporitic or geothermal pool"}, "mechanism": "Nonenzymatic aldol addition/cross-Cannizzaro-like network between glyoxylate and pyruvate forms the C5 alpha-keto diacid alpha-ketoglutarate.", "reasoning": "Directly based on the nonenzymatic ancestral Krebs-cycle analog where glyoxylate and pyruvate generate alpha-ketoglutarate under mild acidic warm conditions; mineral surfaces here are included as concentrators required by the network schema, not because the original report required them (Stubbs et al., 2020; Mayer & Moran, 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamic acid", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K to 323K", "pressure": "moderate to high H2 partial pressure", "catalyst": "FeS/FeS2 analog mineral catalysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "ammonium present; pH near 8 for high-yield Ni systems, with FeS-based precedent for hydrothermal reductive amination"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia adds to the alpha-keto acid followed by mineral-assisted reduction of the imine/iminium to the alpha-amino acid glutamate.", "reasoning": "This step is the best-established prebiotic route to glutamate. Kaur et al. showed alpha-ketoglutarate reductive amination to glutamate at 22C, pH 8 with H2 and Ni/SiO2-Al2O3; earlier FeS/H2S and FeS/Fe(OH)2 work established hydrothermal mineral reductive amination of alpha-oxo acids. The network uses FeS/pyrite-class hydrothermal minerals to satisfy the required environment-mineral constraint while retaining literature grounding (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; Kaur et al., 2024; Nogal et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate with glycine to glutamic acid", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_009", "mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Al3+ in solution; mineral surfaces as concentrators", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 5; metal-ion-catalyzed transamination regime"}, "mechanism": "Amino transfer from glycine to alpha-ketoglutarate forms glutamate within a nonenzymatic transamination network, with glyoxylate regenerated.", "reasoning": "Directly based on the ancestral Krebs-cycle analog showing alpha-ketoglutarate plus glycine gives glutamate in 44% yield at 80C and pH 5 with Al3+ catalysis; glyoxylate is regenerated within the network. Surface minerals are included as concentration/templating agents required by the schema, though soluble Al3+ is the key catalyst in the literature (Degani & Halmann, 1967; Stubbs et al., 2020; Muchowska et al., 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface HCN-based formation of succinic semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-photochemical mineral assistance", "aqueous": "true", "other": "electric discharge/photochemical atmosphere-ocean transfer analog; strongly reducing/anoxic"}, "mechanism": "HCN-rich photochemical and atmospheric chemistry generates higher aldehydes including C4 carbonyls that partition into aqueous surface reservoirs.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies succinic semialdehyde as the required Strecker aldehyde precursor for glutamate, and Miller-type discharge chemistry is the best-supported source of C4 aldehydes/semialdehydes in prebiotic inventories, although no direct dedicated prebiotic synthesis of this precursor was demonstrated. This connecting step is therefore literature-motivated but partly speculative (Miller, 1955; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface Strecker synthesis of glutamate aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration in aqueous pool", "aqueous": "true", "other": "classical Strecker regime in anoxic waters"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde reacts with ammonia to form an imine/hemiaminal, then cyanide addition gives the alpha-aminonitrile precursor to glutamate.", "reasoning": "This is the literature-supported mechanistic logic for Miller-Urey amino acid synthesis, specifically extended to glutamate via the required aldehyde succinic semialdehyde. The report notes that this exact glutamate Strecker route remains plausible but not directly demonstrated from prebiotically sourced succinic semialdehyde, so this step is necessary but partly speculative (Miller, 1955; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Surface hydrolysis of glutamate aminonitrile to glutamic acid", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted hydrolysis/concentration", "aqueous": "true", "other": "extended aqueous aging or wet-dry cycling"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolyzes through amide intermediates to the corresponding amino acid glutamic acid.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of Strecker aminonitriles to amino acids is the accepted downstream step in spark-discharge amino acid synthesis and explains glutamate recovery after hydrolysis-based analyses. Specific isolation of glutamate aminonitrile has not been reported in the cited studies, so this node is a mechanistic reconstruction required to connect literature routes (Miller, 1955; Johnson et al., 2008; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Surface hydrolysis of HCN polymer to glutamic acid", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV exposure and mineral adsorption", "aqueous": "true", "other": "HCN oligomerization/polymer hydrolysis in acidic or basic workup"}, "mechanism": "HCN oligomerization yields polymeric nitrile-rich solids that release amino acids including glutamic acid upon hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "Directly grounded in the classic HCN polymer literature and later reviews showing glutamic acid among hydrolysis products of HCN-derived polymers, while acknowledging product assignments can be analytically challenging (Matthews & Moser, 1967; Ferris, Sanchez & Orgel, 1966-1978; Ruiz-Bermejo et al., 2013; Cleaves et al., 2010)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Biochemical/prebiotic amidation of glutamic acid to glutamine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none demonstrated", "aqueous": "true", "other": "speculative cyanate-activated amidation in concentrated pool; competing cyclization to pyroglutamate expected"}, "mechanism": "Putative activation of the gamma-carboxyl of glutamic acid by cyanate-derived mixed anhydride or intramolecular anhydride chemistry followed by ammonolysis to give the side-chain amide.", "reasoning": "This is the unresolved bottleneck. The literature states that no prebiotic experiment has demonstrated glutamine formation, and cyanate-mediated activation of dicarboxylic acids is identified as the most promising but undemonstrated route. This reaction is therefore explicitly speculative and included only because the user requested a network to glutamine (Danger et al., 2012; Leman et al., 2004; Weber & Miller, 1981; Higgs & Pudritz, 2009; de Carvalho Fernandes et al., 2022)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal carbon fixation to reductive amination route", "description": "CO2 is reduced hydrothermally to formate and acetate, extended to pyruvate, coupled with glyoxylate on the surface to alpha-ketoglutarate, then reductively aminated to glutamate and speculatively amidated to glutamine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Pyruvate-glyoxylate aldol plus transamination route", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate feeds surface aldol formation of alpha-ketoglutarate, which undergoes nonenzymatic transamination with glycine to glutamate before speculative amidation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Formate-assisted protometabolic route", "description": "Hydrothermal formate enters a surface protometabolic network to glyoxylate, then alpha-ketoglutarate, glutamate, and finally speculative glutamine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Strecker route from HCN and succinic semialdehyde", "description": "Surface HCN chemistry supplies succinic semialdehyde, which undergoes Strecker synthesis to glutamate aminonitrile and hydrolysis to glutamate, followed by speculative amidation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "HCN polymer hydrolysis route", "description": "HCN oligomerization/polymerization produces glutamic acid upon hydrolysis, which then faces the unresolved amidation bottleneck to glutamine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Alpha-ketoglutarate reductive amination minimal route", "description": "Once alpha-ketoglutarate is available from pyruvate and glyoxylate, hydrothermal reductive amination gives glutamate, followed by speculative cyanate-mediated amidation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Alpha-ketoglutarate transamination minimal route", "description": "Alpha-ketoglutarate formed on the surface is converted to glutamate by glycine-dependent transamination, then speculatively amidated.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface mixed route via acetate and pyruvate", "description": "A longer mixed-environment path in which hydrothermal acetate and pyruvate production feed surface alpha-ketoglutarate formation and then glutamate synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate to surface alpha-ketoglutarate to transamination route", "description": "Hydrothermal pyruvate enters the surface aldol network to alpha-ketoglutarate and then the transamination branch to glutamate and speculative glutamine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Convergent glutamate pool route", "description": "Multiple glutamate-producing routes converge into a common glutamate reservoir, any of which could in principle feed the unresolved final amidation step to glutamine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_006", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_011"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_008", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_006", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_004"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "incoming_reactions": [], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 104058.39323997498, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T14:41:41.972071", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Glutamine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network is literature-guided and explicitly reflects that glutamine is not a demonstrated prebiotic product. The network therefore builds a connected bipartite synthesis graph in which multiple experimentally supported routes converge on glutamic acid through the central hub alpha-ketoglutarate, while the final conversion to glutamine is represented only as speculative, low-plausibility amidation chemistry motivated by cyanate/phosphate activation analogies discussed in the literature. Hydrothermal chemistry supplies formate, acetate, pyruvate, and reductive amination routes; surface chemistry supplies glyoxylate, HCN-derived precursors, Strecker-type access to glutamate, and activation chemistry; biochemical/prebiotic settings host transamination, condensation, and the undemonstrated final amidation. The graph contains 10 distinct pathway variants to the target, most of which share the same unresolved final bottleneck from glutamic acid to glutamine.\n\nMOLECULES (15 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_004: CH2O2 (formate/formic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: C2H4O2 (acetate/acetic acid) [intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C3H4O3 (pyruvate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C2H2O3 (glyoxylate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C5H6O5 (alpha-ketoglutarate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C5H9NO4 (glutamic acid/glutamate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C2H5NO2 (glycine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_011: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C4H6O3 (succinic semialdehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C5H8N2O2 (glutamate aminonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: CHNO (cyanate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C5H8N2O3 (glutamine) [target]\n\nREACTIONS (12 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_004 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_004, mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_005 (Hydrothermal reduction from formate/CO2 to acetate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_001, mol_002, mol_005 -> mol_006 (Hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_004, mol_010 -> mol_007 (Surface generation of glyoxylate from simple amino acid precursor network) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_007, mol_006 -> mol_008 (Surface aldol coupling of glyoxylate and pyruvate to alpha-ketoglutarate) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_008, mol_003, mol_002 -> mol_009 (Hydrothermal reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamic acid) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_007: mol_008, mol_010 -> mol_009, mol_007 (Surface transamination of alpha-ketoglutarate with glycine to glutamic acid) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_011, mol_004, mol_005 -> mol_012 (Surface HCN-based formation of succinic semialdehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_012, mol_003, mol_011 -> mol_013 (Surface Strecker synthesis of glutamate aminonitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_013 -> mol_009 (Surface hydrolysis of glutamate aminonitrile to glutamic acid) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_011 -> mol_009 (Surface hydrolysis of HCN polymer to glutamic acid) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_009, mol_003, mol_014 -> mol_015 (Biochemical/prebiotic amidation of glutamic acid to glutamine) [Biochemical]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Hydrothermal carbon fixation to reductive amination route (7 steps)\n  - P2: Pyruvate-glyoxylate aldol plus transamination route (5 steps)\n  - P3: Formate-assisted protometabolic route (5 steps)\n  - P4: Strecker route from HCN and succinic semialdehyde (4 steps)\n  - P5: HCN polymer hydrolysis route (2 steps)\n  - P6: Alpha-ketoglutarate reductive amination minimal route (3 steps)\n  - P7: Alpha-ketoglutarate transamination minimal route (3 steps)\n  - P8: Hydrothermal-to-surface mixed route via acetate and pyruvate (6 steps)\n  - P9: Hydrothermal pyruvate to surface alpha-ketoglutarate to transamination route (4 steps)\n  - P10: Convergent glutamate pool route (5 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_004, mol_006, mol_008, mol_009, mol_011\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 4\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of glutamine remains an unsolved origin-of-life puzzle\n\n**Glutamine (C\u2085H\u2081\u2080N\u2082O\u2083) has never been detected in any prebiotic synthesis experiment or meteorite analysis**, making it one of the most challenging amino acids to account for in origin-of-life scenarios. While its parent molecule glutamic acid ranks among the top four prebiotically abundant amino acids \u2014 consistently produced in Miller-Urey experiments, found in carbonaceous chondrites, and accessible through multiple abiotic pathways \u2014 glutamine's side-chain amide bond introduces a thermodynamic and kinetic barrier that no demonstrated prebiotic chemistry has overcome. This asymmetry between glutamic acid availability and glutamine absence encapsulates a fundamental tension in prebiotic chemistry: the dicarboxylic amino acids form readily, but their amide derivatives require enzymatic activation that likely only emerged after the origin of life itself. The consensus view, supported by the amino acid chronology work of Higgs and Pudritz (*Astrobiology*, 2009), classifies glutamine as a \"late\" amino acid \u2014 one of the final additions to the genetic code, incorporated only after glutamine synthetase or a primitive precursor enzyme evolved.\n\n## Multiple routes to glutamic acid converge, but none reach glutamine\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis landscape for glutamic acid is surprisingly rich, with at least five experimentally demonstrated pathways producing this C\u2085 dicarboxylic amino acid from simple starting materials. Each route has distinct strengths and limitations, yet all share a common endpoint: they produce glutamic acid, not glutamine.\n\n**Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate** represents the most efficient and biologically relevant pathway. Kaur, Moran, and colleagues demonstrated in 2024 (*Chem*, 10:1528\u20131540) that H\u2082 gas drives nonenzymatic reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate using Ni/SiO\u2082-Al\u2082O\u2083 catalysts at just **22\u00b0C and pH 8**, achieving combined amino acid yields of **6\u201384%** depending on catalyst and conditions. Remarkably, ground Aletai iron meteorite also catalyzed this reaction, directly linking meteoritic minerals to amino acid synthesis. Nogal and colleagues (*Organic Chemistry Frontiers*, 2024) showed NADH-mediated reductive amination yielding **8% glutamate** at 72 hours. The foundational work by Hafenbradl, Keller, W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, and Stetter (*Tetrahedron Letters*, 1995) first demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-oxo acids using the FeS/H\u2082S system, while Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (*Tetrahedron Letters*, 2003) confirmed amino acid formation from keto-acid precursors using freshly precipitated FeS or Fe(OH)\u2082 with ammonia.\n\n**Metal-catalyzed transamination** offers another high-yield route. Stubbs, Krishnamurthy, and Springsteen demonstrated a metal-free ancestral Krebs cycle analog in which \u03b1-ketoglutarate reacts with glycine to produce **glutamate in 44% yield** at 80\u00b0C, pH 5, with Al\u00b3\u207a catalysis (*Nature Chemistry*, 2020, 12:1016\u20131022). Degani and Halmann (*Nature*, 1967) had earlier shown non-enzymatic transamination at 85\u00b0C catalyzed by Al\u00b3\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a, Cu\u00b2\u207a, and Fe\u00b3\u207a ions. Muchowska, Varma, and Moran (*Journal of the American Chemical Society*, 2021) systematically investigated metal-ion-catalyzed transamination under physiological conditions, confirming Cu\u00b2\u207a, Ni\u00b2\u207a, Co\u00b2\u207a, and V\u2075\u207a as effective catalysts. The critical prerequisite \u2014 prebiotic \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2014 is now well-established: Stubbs and Springsteen showed it forms from glyoxylate and pyruvate via aldol and cross-Cannizzaro chemistry at pH 4.5 and 70\u00b0C without metal catalysts.\n\n**Miller-Urey spark discharge experiments** consistently produce glutamic acid, though at low yields. Miller's 1955 analysis (*Journal of the American Chemical Society*, 77:2351\u20132361) reported **6 \u00b5mol glutamic acid from 710 mmol carbon input (0.051% yield)**, roughly 100-fold lower than glycine. The 2008 reanalysis of Miller's archived volcanic apparatus vials by Johnson, Cleaves, and Bada (*Science*, 322:404) detected glutamic acid among 22 amino acids using modern HPLC and LC-ToF-MS. Parker and colleagues (*Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, 2011, 108:5526\u20135531) found glutamic acid in Miller's 1958 H\u2082S-containing experiment alongside 23 amino acids total. The mechanism proceeds via Strecker synthesis in the aqueous phase: electric discharge generates HCN and C\u2084 aldehydes (including succinic semialdehyde) in the gas phase, which dissolve and react with ammonia to form aminonitriles that hydrolyze to amino acids.\n\n**HCN oligomerization** provides yet another pathway. Matthews and Moser (*Science*, 1967) demonstrated that poly-\u03b1-cyanoglycine from HCN converts to heteropolypeptides hydrolyzable to glycine, alanine, valine, aspartic acid, and **glutamic acid**. Ruiz-Bermejo and colleagues (*Life*, 2013) confirmed in a comprehensive review that HCN polymers yield 12 of 20 protein amino acids upon hydrolysis. However, Cleaves and coworkers (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2010) cautioned that some amino acid identifications from HCN polymers require more rigorous confirmation with high-resolution LC-MS.\n\n**Pyrite photocatalysis** represents an exciting recent development. A 2024 study in *Nature Communications* showed that natural pyrite catalyzes photocatalytic reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids \u2014 including \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamic acid \u2014 under Xe lamp irradiation at **20\u00b0C**, with the product showing enantiomeric excess (D-form, 14.5\u201342.4% ee). The cyanosulfidic framework of Patel, Sutherland, and colleagues (*Nature Chemistry*, 2015, 7:301\u2013307) primarily accesses C\u2082\u2013C\u2083 amino acid precursors and has not directly demonstrated glutamic acid synthesis, though the emerging connection between Bucherer-Bergs chemistry and \u03b1-keto acid metabolism (Pulletikurti, Krishnamurthy *et al.*, *Nature Chemistry*, 2022, 14:1142\u20131150) may eventually bridge this gap.\n\n## Critical intermediates reveal a bottleneck at C\u2085 carbon chain assembly\n\nThe key intermediates on the path to glutamine form a branching network whose central node is **\u03b1-ketoglutarate (2-oxoglutarate)**, the universal biological precursor to glutamic acid and the metabolic gateway for nitrogen assimilation.\n\n\u03b1-Ketoglutarate occupies a unique position in prebiotic chemistry. Mayer and Moran (*Angewandte Chemie International Edition*, 2022, 61:e202212237) found it to be the **least intrinsically reactive** of the Krebs cycle keto acids toward reductive amination \u2014 a finding they argue explains why biology selected it as the thermodynamic anchor of the transamination landscape. Its prebiotic formation from glyoxylate and pyruvate through aldol chemistry, as demonstrated by Stubbs and Springsteen's group, mirrors the biological reductive TCA cycle and supports Morowitz and Smith's metabolism-first hypothesis (*Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, 2004, 101:13168\u201313173). Ter-Ovanessian, Krishnamurthy, and Springsteen (*Angewandte Chemie International Edition*, 2025, 64:e202507248) showed that serine and glycine in the presence of phosphate and Cu\u00b2\u207a generate glyoxylate and pyruvate, which then undergo aldol chemistry to form \u03b1-ketoglutarate, closing a plausible prebiotic cycle.\n\nFor the Strecker route, the required aldehyde precursor is **succinic semialdehyde** (4-oxobutanoic acid), a C\u2084 aldehyde with a terminal carboxyl group. This molecule is far less common in prebiotic inventories than formaldehyde or acetaldehyde, which limits the Strecker pathway's plausibility for glutamic acid compared to simpler amino acids. The reaction proceeds through a hemiaminal intermediate to an \u03b1-aminonitrile, whose hydrolysis yields glutamic acid. No direct experimental demonstration of glutamic acid Strecker synthesis from prebiotically sourced succinic semialdehyde has been reported.\n\n**HCN-derived intermediates** \u2014 the dimer (iminoacetonitrile), trimer (aminomalononitrile), and tetramer (diaminomaleonitrile, DAMN) \u2014 serve as branch points for diverse prebiotic products including purines, pyrimidines, and amino acids. Higher HCN oligomers and the polymeric material often called \"azulmic acid\" hydrolyze under acidic or basic conditions to release amino acids including glutamic acid, though the precise molecular pathway from HCN polymer to C\u2085 amino acids remains poorly characterized. Ferris, Sanchez, and Orgel established the foundational HCN polymerization chemistry in a series of publications from 1966 to 1978 (*Journal of Molecular Biology*, *Journal of Molecular Evolution*).\n\n## Environmental settings impose strict constraints on glutamine survival\n\nThe thermal fragility of glutamine creates a narrow window of viable prebiotic environments. **Glutamine is the least thermally stable of all 20 protein amino acids**, with solid-state decomposition beginning at just **185\u00b0C** (Weiss, Muth, Drumm, and Kirchner, *BMC Biophysics*, 2018). In aqueous solution at 37\u00b0C, free glutamine loses approximately **10% per day** to pyroglutamic acid formation and deamidation (Hamilton, *Biochemical Journal*, 1962). Even at 22\u201324\u00b0C, degradation proceeds at **0.23% per day** in water at pH 6.5 (Khan *et al.*, *Clinical Nutrition*, 2006). The activation energy for this degradation is **98.7 kJ/mol (23.6 kcal/mol)** at pH 6.41 (Arii *et al.*, *European Journal of Pharmaceutical Sciences*, 1999).\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents** offer the most favorable setting for glutamic acid synthesis, though glutamine stability remains problematic even here. The Lost City hydrothermal field operates at **40\u201375\u00b0C and pH 9\u20139.8** (Kelley *et al.*, 2001), with fluids rich in H\u2082 (1\u201315 mmol/kg). The Russell-Martin model proposes that life arose in FeS/NiS-walled compartments where cool, CO\u2082-rich Hadean ocean water met hot, alkaline hydrothermal fluid. Kitadai (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2015) calculated that amino acid synthesis from CO\u2082, H\u2082, NH\u2083, and H\u2082S is energetically favorable at vent-ocean interfaces, with optimal synthesis temperatures around **50\u00b0C** in mixing zones. Serpentinization \u2014 the reaction of olivine with water producing serpentine, brucite, magnetite, and H\u2082 \u2014 generated an estimated **10\u00b9\u00b9 mol H\u2082/year** during the Precambrian (Sleep *et al.*, *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, 2004). Awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe) nanoparticles formed during serpentinization catalyze H\u2082-dependent CO\u2082 fixation to formate, acetate, and pyruvate at 100\u00b0C (Preiner *et al.*, 2020; Beyazay *et al.*, *Angewandte Chemie*, 2023).\n\n**Black smoker vents (300\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20135)** are net destroyers of amino acids. Bada, Miller, and Zhao (*Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere*, 1995, 25:111\u2013118) demonstrated that amino acids are irreversibly destroyed at 240\u00b0C, with glutamine expected to survive only seconds to minutes at such temperatures. At 200\u2013250\u00b0C, aspartate and serine decompose within 20 minutes; glycine and alanine persist somewhat longer but still degrade within hours (Dalai *et al.*, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 2013). High pressures (1.0\u20135.5 GPa) can stabilize simpler amino acids (Ohara *et al.*, *Astrobiology*, 2007), but this protection is unlikely to extend to the labile amide group of glutamine.\n\n**Wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools** at 60\u201390\u00b0C drives condensation reactions and could concentrate reactants, but also accelerates glutamine decomposition. Campbell and colleagues (*Nature Communications*, 2019) showed that deliquescent minerals mediate glycine oligomerization during wet-dry cycles with yields 10-fold higher than controls. For glutamine, the drying phase could in principle drive amidation of glutamic acid with ammonia, but the same heating promotes competing pyroglutamic acid cyclization.\n\n## Iron-sulfur minerals and nickel catalysts drive the most prebiotically relevant reactions\n\nMineral catalysts are essential for nearly every demonstrated prebiotic route to glutamic acid, and understanding their roles illuminates both opportunities and limitations for glutamine formation.\n\n**Nickel-based catalysts** deliver the highest yields for reductive amination. The Kaur and Moran 2024 study used Ni/SiO\u2082-Al\u2082O\u2083 (10 mol%) to convert \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate at room temperature with H\u2082 gas and ammonium ions. With Pd catalyst, selectivity exceeded **5:1 amino acid over hydroxy acid** with yields of **52\u201388%**. The native nickel alloy awaruite (Ni\u2083Fe), produced naturally during serpentinization, catalyzes the same H\u2082-dependent CO\u2082 fixation reactions that produce TCA cycle intermediates including pyruvate and potentially \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This connects the mineral inventory of serpentinizing systems directly to the amino acid synthesis network.\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** underpin the W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user iron-sulfur world hypothesis. Pyrite (FeS\u2082) serves as both an electron source (via oxidative formation from FeS + H\u2082S) and a catalytic surface. Freshly precipitated FeS drives reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids with ammonia (Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, *Tetrahedron Letters*, 2003). Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), whose crystal structure resembles biological [4Fe-4S] clusters, and mackinawite (FeS), whose layered structure mirrors [2Fe-2S] ferredoxin clusters, are proposed as ancestral catalysts for electron transfer reactions (Russell and Martin; Bonfio *et al.*, *Nature Chemistry*, 2017). Iron oxyhydroxides with mixed Fe(II)/Fe(III) valence states catalyze reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine at 70\u00b0C and alkaline pH (Barge *et al.*, *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, 2019, 116:4828\u20134833), though extension to \u03b1-ketoglutarate has not yet been tested.\n\n**Clay minerals** serve primarily as concentrators and polymerization catalysts rather than synthesis catalysts. Montmorillonite adsorbs amino acids from dilute solution, with glutamic acid binding through both backbone and side-chain carboxylate groups (Sverjensky group, NASA Astrobiology Institute). Fe\u00b2\u207a-exchanged montmorillonite shows superior adsorption for biomolecules. Layered double hydroxides (LDH) concentrate, align, and template amino acids during wetting-drying cycles, with charge redistribution on the LDH surface activating carboxylate groups for peptide bond formation (Gr\u00e9goire *et al.*, *Nature Communications*, 2017). Notably, montmorillonite also catalyzes **deamination** of glutamic acid (Naidja and Siffert, *Clay Minerals*, 1989; Mortland, *Journal of Molecular Catalysis*, 1984), meaning it could destroy glutamine as readily as it might help form it.\n\n**No mineral catalyst has been shown to facilitate the specific amidation of glutamic acid's \u03b3-carboxyl to produce glutamine.** This remains a critical gap in the experimental literature.\n\n## Meteorite and experimental data consistently exclude glutamine\n\nThe experimental record paints a remarkably consistent picture. Across decades of prebiotic synthesis experiments spanning spark discharge, HCN polymerization, UV photolysis, proton irradiation, and hydrothermal simulation, **glutamine has never been identified among the products**. This absence is not merely an analytical artifact \u2014 though acid hydrolysis during sample workup would convert glutamine to glutamic acid, modern HPLC and LC-MS methods used in reanalyses (Johnson *et al.*, 2008; Parker *et al.*, 2011) would have detected glutamine had it been present in significant quantities before hydrolysis.\n\nThe **Murchison meteorite** (CM2 carbonaceous chondrite) contains glutamic acid at approximately **2\u20137 \u00b5g/g**, making it one of the more abundant protein amino acids in the meteorite alongside glycine (~5 \u00b5g/g). Cronin's group identified 52 amino acids in Murchison over the course of the 1970s\u20131990s. Engel and Nagy (*Nature*, 1982) measured a D/L glutamic acid ratio of 0.3, initially interpreted as an L-excess, though Glavin and colleagues (2020) later showed that L-glutamic acid excesses of 56\u201373% in the Aguas Zarcas CM2 meteorite are likely terrestrial contamination, with the D-glutamic acid component being indigenous. Glutamine has **not been detected** in any meteorite analysis.\n\nIn spark discharge experiments, glutamic acid yields follow an exponential decline with carbon number that is a universal feature of prebiotic amino acid synthesis: in Miller's 1955 data, glycine (630 \u00b5mol) exceeds glutamic acid (6 \u00b5mol) by roughly **100-fold**. Sagan and Khare (*Science*, 1971) produced glutamic acid via UV photolysis of CH\u2084/C\u2082H\u2086/NH\u2083/H\u2082O/H\u2082S, while Kobayashi's extensive proton irradiation work (*Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*, 1990; *Life*, 2023) demonstrated amino acid formation from weakly reducing atmospheres, with glycine always dominant and C\u2085 acids in trace amounts.\n\nHiggs and Pudritz's meta-analysis (*Astrobiology*, 2009, 9:483\u2013490) established the consensus ranking of prebiotic amino acid abundance: **Gly > Ala > Asp > Glu > Val > Ser > Ile > Leu > Pro > Thr**. Glutamine falls among the \"late\" amino acids (grouped with Asn, Cys, Tyr, Met, Trp) that are universally absent from prebiotic contexts. This ranking correlates strongly with thermodynamic favorability of formation (\u0394G_surf), confirming that the absence of glutamine reflects fundamental chemistry rather than experimental oversight.\n\n## The amide bond problem and glutamine's quadruple instability\n\nConverting glutamic acid to glutamine requires forming an amide bond between the \u03b3-carboxyl group and ammonia \u2014 a reaction that is thermodynamically uphill by approximately **+14\u201316 kJ/mol** in aqueous solution, analogous to peptide bond formation. In biology, this barrier is overcome by ATP-dependent glutamine synthetase (GS; EC 6.3.1.2), which proceeds through a **\u03b3-glutamyl phosphate intermediate**. GS is among the oldest functioning genes studied: de Carvalho Fernandes and colleagues (*Evolution*, 2022, 76:605\u2013622) showed that gene duplications gave rise to three GS groups **before the Last Universal Common Ancestor (LUCA)**, underscoring the antiquity and essentiality of this reaction.\n\nSeveral prebiotic activating agents could theoretically substitute for ATP, but none has been demonstrated to produce glutamine:\n\n- **Carbonyl sulfide (COS)**: Leman, Orgel, and Ghadiri (*Science*, 2004, 306:283\u2013286) achieved up to 80% peptide yields via N-carboxyanhydride intermediates. COS primarily activates \u03b1-amino groups for peptide bonds, not side-chain carboxyls, though \u03b3-carboxyl activation is theoretically possible.\n- **Cyanate (OCN\u207b)**: Danger, Pascal, and colleagues (*Amino Acids*, 2012, 42:2331\u20132341) showed cyanate activates dicarboxylic acids through intramolecular anhydride formation. For glutamic acid, a cyclic glutaric anhydride intermediate could preferentially involve the \u03b3-carboxyl, offering potential selectivity \u2014 the most promising pathway identified, but **undemonstrated experimentally**.\n- **Cyanamide (H\u2082N-CN)** and **polyphosphates**: Classical condensing agents that can drive amide bond formation but with yields typically below 1\u20132% and poor selectivity between \u03b1- and \u03b3-carboxyls.\n\nGlutamine faces a **quadruple instability** under prebiotic conditions that makes accumulation nearly impossible without enzymatic protection:\n\n1. **Deamidation** to glutamic acid + NH\u2083, proceeding through a glutarimide intermediate at neutral-to-alkaline pH (half-lives of **600\u201320,000 days** in peptide contexts at 37\u00b0C; Robinson and Robinson, *Journal of Peptide Research*, 2004)\n2. **Cyclization** to pyroglutamic acid via intramolecular attack of the \u03b1-amino group on the \u03b3-amide \u2014 the dominant degradation pathway for free glutamine\n3. **Racemization** to D-glutamine (slower than deamidation, with activation energies of 28\u201330 kcal/mol)\n4. **Decarboxylation** to 4-aminobutyramide + CO\u2082 (significant only above 200\u00b0C)\n\nThe selectivity problem compounds these difficulties: glutamic acid's \u03b3-carboxyl (pKa 4.25) preferentially reacts with its own \u03b1-amino group to form pyroglutamic acid rather than with external ammonia to form glutamine. This intramolecular cyclization, well-documented by Yu and colleagues (*Journal of Pharmaceutical and Biomedical Analysis*, 2006), represents the single greatest chemical obstacle to prebiotic glutamine synthesis.\n\n## Glutamine was likely a late evolutionary invention\n\nThe combined evidence from prebiotic chemistry, geochemistry, and comparative genomics converges on a clear conclusion: glutamine was not part of the primordial amino acid repertoire. Weber and Miller (*Journal of Molecular Evolution*, 1981) first argued that the instability of glutamine and asparagine and their absence from prebiotic experiments suggest these amino acids were late additions to biology. The co-evolution hypothesis proposes that glutamine was incorporated into the genetic code only after glutamine synthetase (or a primitive precursor) evolved, enabling enzymatic amidation of the readily available glutamic acid.\n\nThis evolutionary timeline is supported by several lines of evidence. First, the **GDH-GS-GOGAT system** (glutamate dehydrogenase, glutamine synthetase, glutamine-2-oxoglutarate aminotransferase) that manages nitrogen assimilation through the glutamate/glutamine pair is universal across all three domains of life and was present in LUCA in multiple forms. This suggests the glutamic acid \u2192 glutamine conversion was among the earliest enzymatic innovations. Second, asparagine faces identical challenges \u2014 its synthesis depends on glutamine as an amide nitrogen donor (asparagine synthetase: Asp + Gln + ATP \u2192 Asn + Glu + AMP + PPi), making it doubly dependent on glutamine availability and placing it even later in the evolutionary timeline. Third, Trifonov's temporal ordering of genetic code expansion (2004) and Higgs and Pudritz's thermodynamic analysis both independently place glutamine among the final amino acids encoded.\n\nThe most plausible prebiotic scenario envisions early proteins composed of the 10\u201312 \"early\" amino acids (including glutamic acid but not glutamine), with glutamine entering the code only after primitive glutamine synthetase activity emerged \u2014 possibly first as a simple ribozyme or mineral-catalyzed process, then as the sophisticated enzyme observed today. Whether any mineral surface or simple catalyst could have provided even rudimentary \u03b3-carboxyl amidation activity remains an open and experimentally testable question.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of glutamine stands as one of the clearest examples of the gap between simple amino acid chemistry and the full complexity of biology's molecular toolkit. Glutamic acid \u2014 glutamine's precursor \u2014 is accessible through at least five experimentally validated prebiotic routes, with reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate (yielding up to **84%** with Ni catalysis) and metal-catalyzed transamination (yielding **44%** with Al\u00b3\u207a) being the most efficient. The \u03b1-ketoglutarate precursor itself forms from glyoxylate and pyruvate via non-enzymatic analogs of the Krebs cycle. Yet the final step \u2014 selective amidation of glutamic acid's \u03b3-carboxyl with ammonia \u2014 remains undemonstrated under any prebiotic condition. Cyanate-mediated intramolecular anhydride chemistry (Danger and Pascal, 2012) offers the most chemically plausible route to selective \u03b3-activation, but experimental validation is needed. The overarching lesson is that **glutamine's absence from prebiotic inventories is not a failure of experimental detection but a genuine reflection of chemical thermodynamics**: forming and maintaining an amide bond on a dicarboxylic amino acid's side chain in water, against competing cyclization and hydrolysis, represents a challenge that only evolved enzymes have solved.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with iss