     \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.61,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.86,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.18\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.58,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.74,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.2,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.57,\n      \"feedback\": \"HCN polymerization and hydrolysis to amino acid mixtures, including glutamate, are literature-supported at a qualitative level, but the exact mechanistic path is poorly resolved and product identification has historically been less rigorous than in modern work. Surface HCN generation from only CO2 and NH3 is weakly specified and not well matched to canonical reduced-atmosphere discharge chemistry.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_016\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Specify a more realistic atmospheric/feedstock context for HCN generation.\",\n        \"State explicitly that glutamate release from HCN polymer hydrolysis is supported only as part of mixed amino-acid products.\",\n        \"Do not count this as a validated glutamine route.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.61,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.66,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.83,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.18\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.57,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.75,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.76,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.2,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.58,\n      \"feedback\": \"The Strecker logic is chemically valid in general, and glutamic acid appears in Miller-type experiments, but the specific requirement for succinic semialdehyde is a major plausibility bottleneck noted in the literature. Direct experimental support for prebiotic sourcing of this aldehyde and clean glutamate aminonitrile progression is limited.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_012\",\n        \"rxn_016\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Explicitly acknowledge succinic semialdehyde availability as a major unresolved issue.\",\n        \"Avoid overstating direct evidence for glutamate aminonitrile as an isolated prebiotic intermediate.\",\n        \"Preserve this as a low-confidence branch to glutamate only.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.61,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.8,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.42,\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.18\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.63,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.78,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.24,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.61,\n      \"feedback\": \"This route attempts to justify the final amidation through cyanate activation, which is conceptually the most literature-aligned speculative strategy. However, the specific step from formamide to cyanate is weakly supported in the form presented, and no experiment demonstrates cyanate-mediated gamma-amidation of glutamate to glutamine. Upstream glutamate chemistry is strong.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_003\",\n        \"rxn_015\",\n        \"rxn_016\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Tie cyanate chemistry directly to Danger and Pascal style dicarboxylate activation rather than implying established glutamine formation.\",\n        \"Introduce competing intramolecular cyclization to pyroglutamate as a likely side reaction.\",\n        \"Provide a more defensible source of cyanate if this branch is retained.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\"